  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nLk\n=\n\\frac{1}{4\\pi}\n\\oint_{C_1}\n\\oint_{C_2}\n\\frac{\n(\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2)\n\\cdot\n(\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_1\\times \\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_2)\n}{\n|\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2|^3\n}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $C_1$ and $C_2$ be two closed magnetic flux tubes or field-line loops.  \nThe Gauss linking integral measures how many times the two loops wind around one another.\n\nFor points $\\mathbf{r}_1\\in C_1$ and $\\mathbf{r}_2\\in C_2$, the relative displacement is:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe oriented area element generated by the two path differentials is:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_1\\times \\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_2 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nNormalizing by the cubic separation gives the universal linking density:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\n(\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2)\n\\cdot\n(\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_1\\times \\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_2)\n}{\n|\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2|^3\n}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe full linking number is:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nLk\n=\n\\frac{1}{4\\pi}\n\\oint_{C_1}\n\\oint_{C_2}\n\\frac{\n(\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2)\n\\cdot\n(\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_1\\times \\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{r}_2)\n}{\n|\\mathbf{r}_1-\\mathbf{r}_2|^3\n}.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe linking number is integer-valued and topologically stable. It supplies the universal counting rule behind helicity quantisation.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
